      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">
        <p class="lede-p"><strong>Wordtune is the best sentence-level AI rewriter you can buy.</strong> It is also a niche tool — useful inside a larger writing workflow, useless on its own for content marketing or SEO. After 30 days across every paid tier and the free plan, plus interviews with 8 paying customers, here is the honest 2026 verdict and the four situations where Wordtune is genuinely the right call.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-tldr">
          <div class="callout-label">⚡ TL;DR — The 30-second verdict</div>
          <p><strong>Buy Wordtune if</strong> you write a lot of email, reports, sales copy, or essays and want sentence-level rewrites without prompting ChatGPT every time. The Chrome extension is excellent. <strong>Skip Wordtune if</strong> you need full articles, keyword research, or SEO optimisation — Wordtune does none of that. If you want done-for-you SEO content with publishing, theStacc handles 30 articles per month from $99/mo.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">ℹ️ Editorial disclosure</div>
          <p>This review was written and published by theStacc, a competing product in the broader content space. We have a commercial interest as an alternative. Every feature claim and price was verified against Wordtune's public pricing page as of Q2 2026. Note: AI21 Labs reduced active Wordtune development in 2025 to focus on enterprise AI.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="inline-cta">
          <div class="cta-copy">
            <h4>Want full articles, not just rewrites?</h4>
            <p>Get a <strong>free SEO audit</strong> in 24 hours. We'll show you the keywords you're missing, the topics you should rank for, and the content gaps your competitors are exploiting — no sales call, no obligation.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="cta-action">
            <a href="/demo/" class="cta-btn-inline">Get my free audit <span>→</span></a>
            <span class="cta-meta">24-hour delivery · No card</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-stacc">theStacc vs Wordtune — different jobs, honest comparison</h2>
        <p>Wordtune and theStacc do not directly compete on the same job. We compare anyway because writers researching one often consider both.</p>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Feature</th><th>Wordtune</th><th>theStacc</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td>Starting price</td><td class="cell-yes">Free (10 rewrites/day)</td><td>$99/mo</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Sentence-level rewriting</td><td class="cell-yes">Best in category</td><td class="cell-no">Not the job</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Tone adjustment (casual/formal)</td><td class="cell-yes">Built-in, smooth</td><td>Brand voice, not per-sentence</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Full articles written for you</td><td class="cell-no">No — rewrites existing text only</td><td class="cell-yes">30 original articles / month</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Keyword research / SEO optimisation</td><td class="cell-no">None</td><td class="cell-yes">Built into every article</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Auto-publishes to your CMS</td><td class="cell-no">No</td><td class="cell-yes">WordPress · Webflow · Ghost</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Google Business Profile posts</td><td class="cell-no">Not included</td><td class="cell-yes">30 GBP posts / month</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Social media posts</td><td class="cell-no">Not included</td><td class="cell-yes">30 posts / month</td></tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Best for</strong></td><td>Polishing your own writing</td><td><strong>Growing organic traffic</strong></td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p><strong>Where Wordtune wins:</strong> if you write the words yourself and want a faster way to vary phrasing. <strong>Where theStacc wins:</strong> if your job is shipping SEO content at scale without writing it personally. Different jobs.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is Wordtune?</h2>
        <p>Wordtune is an AI rewriting tool built by AI21 Labs, an Israeli generative AI company. Launched in 2020, it has grown to over 10 million users who have collectively generated more than 782 million rewrite suggestions. The product runs as a Chrome extension, web editor, Word add-in, and mobile apps.</p>

        <p>The core feature surface is small and focused:</p>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Rewrite</strong> — paraphrase any selected sentence into 3–5 alternative versions</li>
          <li><strong>Tone</strong> — adjust selected text to casual or formal</li>
          <li><strong>Shorten / Expand</strong> — compress or extend a sentence without losing meaning</li>
          <li><strong>Spices</strong> — generate examples, statistics, counterarguments, or analogies inline</li>
          <li><strong>Summariser</strong> — condenses long-form text (articles, PDFs) into bullet summaries</li>
          <li><strong>AI Assist</strong> — ChatGPT-style prompt for drafting short-form text (Unlimited tier)</li>
        </ol>

        <p>What Wordtune is <em>not</em>: a full-article generator, an SEO tool, a research tool, or a publishing platform. It improves what you already wrote.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">ℹ️ Company background</div>
          <p>AI21 Labs was founded in 2017 in Tel Aviv by Yoav Shoham, Ori Goshen, and Amnon Shashua. The company raised over $336M total, became known for the Jurassic family of large language models, and built Wordtune as a consumer showcase. In April 2025, AI21 publicly reduced Wordtune investment to focus on enterprise AI agents. The product still works and is maintained, but feature shipping has slowed.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="features">Wordtune features — the full 2026 walkthrough</h2>

        <h3>1. Rewrite — the headline feature</h3>
        <p>Select any sentence in the Wordtune editor, Google Docs, Gmail, Notion, or LinkedIn. Wordtune returns 3–5 alternative phrasings. The suggestions are genuinely good — semantically equivalent but stylistically varied. Better than QuillBot in our blind tests, comparable to a thoughtful prompt to ChatGPT.</p>

        <h3>2. Tone control</h3>
        <p>One click toggles between casual and formal. The shift is subtle (vocabulary, contraction usage, sentence rhythm) rather than dramatic. Useful for adapting the same draft to different audiences without rewriting from scratch.</p>

        <h3>3. Shorten / Expand</h3>
        <p>Shorten compresses a sentence while preserving meaning. Expand adds explanatory detail. Shorten is genuinely useful for tightening. Expand frequently adds fluff — use sparingly.</p>

        <h3>4. Spices</h3>
        <p>The most interesting feature. Insert examples, statistics, counterarguments, or analogies into your draft at the cursor. Stats are hit-and-miss accuracy — always verify. Examples and analogies are usually solid.</p>

        <h3>5. Summariser</h3>
        <p>Paste a long article or upload a PDF; Wordtune returns bullet-point key takeaways with links back to the source paragraph. Useful for research and meeting prep.</p>

        <h3>6. AI Assist (Unlimited and Business tiers)</h3>
        <p>A chat interface for drafting short-form content — emails, LinkedIn posts, replies. The output quality is below GPT-4 and Claude. The convenience is being inside the same surface as the rewriter.</p>

        <h2 id="pricing">Wordtune pricing — what it really costs in 2026</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Plan</th><th>Annual / mo</th><th>Monthly</th><th>Rewrites</th><th>AI Assist</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td><strong>Free</strong></td><td>$0</td><td>$0</td><td>10/day</td><td class="cell-no">No</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Plus</strong></td><td>$6.99</td><td>$13.99</td><td>Unlimited</td><td class="cell-no">No</td></tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Unlimited</strong></td><td>$9.99</td><td>$19.99</td><td>Unlimited</td><td class="cell-yes">Included</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Business</strong></td><td>$14.99/user</td><td>$24.99/user</td><td>Unlimited</td><td class="cell-yes">Included + admin</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p>The free plan is genuinely usable — 10 rewrites per day is enough for occasional polishing. Heavy users hit the cap within minutes. Plus is the right entry tier for most writers. Unlimited only makes sense if you want AI Assist.</p>

        <h3>The real cost of using Wordtune for SEO content</h3>
        <p>Wordtune is cheap. The math gets expensive once you need full SEO articles, not just sentence rewrites.</p>

        <div class="cost-calc">
